Affirming forecast. Just want to do a bit of a postmortem. I went and stayed below 10% in this question way back in March 2017, when consensus was still above 70%. Highest I ever was, was 30%, for 2 weeks back in December 2016. I paid very little attention to the daily developments of the Russia / Trump campaign controversy. My prediction was based, in order of importance, on: (i) base rates, such presidential visits usually happen later in the term, and, particularly, several months after the first meeting in a multilateral setting (e.g. the G-20, which was in July this year);
(ii) the actual conflict involving actual bombs (as opposed to just a bunch of talking) in Syria;
(iii) the actual sanctions involving actual economic consequences (as opposed to just a bunch of talking);
(iv) the suggestion of, but non-following through with, a bilateral meeting in Slovenia; 
(v) the bunch of talking around Putin having influenced the election. Arguably (v) could have been important in that, if lots of people are angry that Putin influenced the election, it would put pressure on Trump not to meet with him. I'm sure that happened to some extent. But people forecasting on this question probably pay more attention to politics than the average person, and thus may overestimate how angry the AVERAGE person actually is at this. And politicians only care about the average person. Plus, very little has ACTUALLY HAPPENED on this front beyond a bunch of talking. ONE GUY resigned, and I think that's pretty much it. There's hearings and whatnot but that is extremely easy for Republicans to rationalize away. (Cf. Democrats with Hillary-related hearings.)
